filters the Theorem of Malliaris-Shelah \cite{MiSh:998} fails.
\begin{claim}
\label{s31}
1) There is a complete first order $T$ and $\Delta = \{\varphi(x,y)\}$
where $\varphi(x,y)$ is an atomic formula in ${\mathbb L}(\tau_T)$ such that
$(T,\Delta)$ has ${\rm SOP}_2$ and ${\rm NSOP}_3$.

\noindent
2) Assume $D$ is a regular filter on $\lambda$ and $\mu \le \lambda$
and $M$ is a model of $T$ from part (1).

{\underline{Then}} \, the following conditions are equivlant:
{\medskip\noindent}
\begin{enumerate}
\item[$(a)$]  the filter $D$ is a $(\mu,\aleph_0,1,\Delta,T)$-moral
  filter
{\smallskip\noindent}
\item[$(b)$]  $({\mathbb Q},\le)/D$ has no $(\kappa,\kappa)$-pre-cut
  for any regular $\kappa = {\rm cf}(\kappa) \le \mu$
{\smallskip\noindent}
\item[$(c)$]  in $({}^{\omega >}2,\triangleleft)^\lambda/D$ every
  increasing chain of length $\le \lambda$ has an upper bound.
\end{enumerate}
{\medskip\noindent}
3) $(T,\Delta)$ is not $\triangleleft^{{\rm rp}}_{\lambda,\mu}$-maximal if
$(T,\Delta)$ is the pair constructed in part (1).
\end{claim}

\begin{PROOF}{\ref{s31}}
1) The $T = {\rm Th}(M),\varphi_\ell(x,y) = (x R_\ell y)$ where:
